SIMPLE: redundant
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Redundant
<hw>Re*dun"dant</hw> <pr>(-d<it>a</it>nt)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>redundans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>redundare</ets>:
cf. F. <ets>redondant</ets>. See <er>Redound</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>Exceeding what is natural or necessary; superabundant; exuberant;
<as>as, a <ex>redundant</ex> quantity of bile or food</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Notwithstanding the <qex>redundant</qex> oil in fishes, they do
not increase fat so much as flesh.</q>
<rj><qau>Arbuthnot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Using more worrds or images than are necessary or
useful; pleonastic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Where an suthor is <qex>redundant</qex>, mark those paragraphs to
be retrenched.</q> <rj><qau>I. Watts.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Superfluous; superabundant; excessive; exuberant;
overflowing; plentiful; copious.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Redundantly</ent>⟦br⟧
